1️⃣ JOIN Practice (Real Understanding)
🧠 Mental Model First
JOIN = Match rows from two tables using a condition

👉 Always ask yourself:

What are the tables?
What is the common column?
Example Tables
Students
id	name
1	Akshay
2	Rahul
3	Neha
Marks
student_id	marks
1	85
2	72
3	90
🎯 Interview Question 1

👉 “Get student names with their marks”

SQL Solution
SELECT students.name, marks.marks
FROM students
INNER JOIN marks
ON students.id = marks.student_id;
🧠 Think Like This
students.id = marks.student_id
→ match rows
→ combine columns
Python Equivalent
for s in students:
    for m in marks:
        if s["id"] == m["student_id"]:
            print(s["name"], m["marks"])

👉 SQL replaces nested loops

🎯 Interview Question 2

👉 “Get students who scored more than 80”

SQL
SELECT students.name, marks.marks
FROM students
JOIN marks
ON students.id = marks.student_id
WHERE marks.marks > 80;
🎯 Interview Question 3

👉 “Get all students, even if they have no marks”

SQL (LEFT JOIN)
SELECT students.name, marks.marks
FROM students
LEFT JOIN marks
ON students.id = marks.student_id;
Key Learning
JOIN Type	When to Use
INNER JOIN	Only matching data
LEFT JOIN	Keep all left data
2️⃣ Self JOIN (Very Important Concept)
Simple Idea

Self JOIN = A table joining with itself

👉 Used when data is related within the same table

Real-World Example 🧠
Employees Table
id	name	manager_id
1	Akshay	NULL
2	Rahul	1
3	Neha	1

👉 Question:

“Show employee name with their manager name”

Problem

Manager is also an employee

👉 Same table!

SQL Solution (Self JOIN)
SELECT e.name AS employee, m.name AS manager
FROM employees e
LEFT JOIN employees m
ON e.manager_id = m.id;
Output
employee	manager
Akshay	NULL
Rahul	Akshay
Neha	Akshay
Step-by-Step Understanding
e → employee table
m → same table but acting as manager

e.manager_id = m.id
→ connect employee to manager
Python Connection 🧠
for e in employees:
    for m in employees:
        if e["manager_id"] == m["id"]:
            print(e["name"], m["name"])
Why Self JOIN is Needed

✔ Hierarchical data (manager, parent, category)
✔ Relationships within same table
✔ Very common in interviews

Memory Trick 🧠
Self JOIN = Table joins itself
🔥 Placement Insight

Very common questions:

Q1: What is Self JOIN?

👉 Joining a table with itself

Q2: Why aliases (e, m) are used?

👉 To differentiate same table

Q3: JOIN vs Self JOIN?
JOIN	Self JOIN
Different tables	Same table
Quick Revision (1 Minute)
JOIN → combine tables
INNER JOIN → only matching
LEFT JOIN → all left data

Self JOIN → table joins itself
